So then, whatsoever hitherto was
of the fathers delivered to the worlde
by worde of mouth, & as it were from
hand to hand, that was first of all put
into writing by the holy man Moses,
together with those thinges, which
were done in al the time of Moses life,
by the space of 120. yeeres. And y his e
simation might be ye greater through
out all the world, among all men, and
in all ages, and that none shoulde but
know, that the writinges of Moses
were the very word of God it self, Mo
ses was furnished and as it were con
secrated, by God with signes, & won
ders to bee marveiled at in deed, which
the almighty by the hande, that is, by
the ministerye of Moses did bring to
passe: & verily, he wrought them not
in any corner of the world, or place un
knowen, but in Egypt, the mast flouri
shing and renowmed kingdom of that
age.

Those miracles were greater and farre more by many, than that they ca be here rehearsed in few wordes: ney, ther is it needful to repeate the, because you, deerely beloved, are not unskilfull or ignorat of them at al. After that al so, God by other meanes procured au thoritie to Moses. For many and often times, God had communication with Moses: & amongst the rest of his talke said he, Behold, I will come to thee in a thicke cloude, that the people maye heare me talking with thee, and may beleeve thee for evermore. Neither was the Lorde there with
content, but commanded Moses to cal
together all the people, sire hundreth
thousand men, I say, with their wives
and children. They are called out to
the mount Sina, where God appea
reth in a wonderfull & terrible fashis,
and he himelfe preaching to the con
gregation, doth rehearse uuto them the
ten commandements.
But the people being terrified with
the majesty of God, doth pray and be
seech, that God himselfe would no more
afterward preach to the congregation
with his owne mouth, saying, that it
were enough if he would use Moses as
an interpreter to them, and by him
speake to the Churth. The most high
God did like the offer, and after that,
he spake to the people by Moses, what
soever he woulde have done. And for
because that the people was a stifner
ked people, & by keeping company with
Idolaters in Egypt, was not a little
corrupted. Moses now beganne to set
downe in writing, those things which
ye holy fathers by tradition had taught
& the thing also which the Lord had re
vealed unto him. The cause why hee
wrote them was, least peradventure,
by oblivion, by continuance of time
and obstinacie of a people so slowe to
beleeve, they might either perishe, or
else be corrupted. The Lorde also set
Moses an erample to folow. For what
soever God hath spoken to the Church
in Mount Sina, ye same did he streight
way after, write with his own singer
in two tables of stone, as hee had with
his finger from the beginning of the
world writte the same in the hearts of
the fathers. Afterward also in plaine
words he commanded Moses to write
whatsoever the Lorde had revealed.
Moses obeyed the Lordes commande
ment, & wrote them. The holie Ghost
